# Stack

- FastAPI for API layer, aiogram for Telegram bots
- SQLAlchemy 2 (async) for DB, Alembic for migrations
- Pydantic v2 for all data validation — never raw dicts in API handlers
- pytest + pytest-cov for tests, coverage must not drop below 80%
- ruff for linting — fix all warnings before committing

# Code style

- Always add type hints on all functions and class attributes
- Use async/await consistently — never mix sync DB calls in async handlers
- Prefer early returns over deeply nested if-blocks
- Never use bare `except` — always catch specific exceptions (ValueError, HTTPException, etc.)
- Never use `print()` for debugging — use `logging` module
- Never hardcode secrets — all config via .env + pydantic-settings BaseSettings

# Architecture

- Split code into layers: routers → services → repositories → models
- Routers only handle HTTP: parse input, call service, return response
- Business logic lives in services, never in routers or models
- Each module does one thing — if file exceeds 200 lines, split it

# Naming

- snake_case for functions and variables
- PascalCase for classes and Pydantic models  
- SCREAMING_SNAKE_CASE for constants
- Prefix private methods and attributes with _
- Test files: test_<module_name>.py

# Git commits (Conventional Commits)

- feat: add JWT refresh token rotation
- fix: handle expired token in auth middleware
- test: add coverage for book search endpoint
- refactor: extract search logic to BookService
- docs: update README with CI/CD section
- chore: bump dependencies

# Don't

- Don't add TODO comments — implement fully or raise NotImplementedError with message
- Don't write tests that mock everything — use real DB in tests (testcontainers or pytest fixtures)
- Don't put business logic in Alembic migration files
- Don't commit .env files — only .env.example with placeholder values
